    <section id="programs">
      <div class="shell">
        <div class="section-head">
          <span class="tag">Programs</span>
          <h2>Three lanes. One serious system.</h2>
          <p>
            CMS is not one generic template in a new coat of paint. Each track has its own purpose,
            training feel, and engine behavior.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid">
          <article class="card">
            <h3>Bench Specialization</h3>
            <p>
              This is for lifters who want pressing strength to move now. CMS supports focused bench work,
              weak-point-aware exercise swaps, and a cleaner path from volume to strength to test week.
            </p>
            <ul class="bullet-list">
              <li>Lockout, mid-range, and off-chest weakness logic</li>
              <li>Bench-centered block sequencing with productive weeks and deload timing</li>
              <li>Accessory selection that serves the main lift instead of distracting from it</li>
            </ul>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>Jacked & Strong</h3>
            <p>
              Jacked and Strong hits a sweet spot a lot of lifters want:
              measurable barbell progress and enough hypertrophy work to actually build a physique.
            </p>
            <ul class="bullet-list">
              <li>Five-week hypertrophy and four-week strength blocks</li>
              <li>Machine and accessory work that supports recovery instead of burying it</li>
              <li>Size and numbers at the same time</li>
            </ul>
          </article>

          <article class="card">
            <h3>SBD</h3>
            <p>
              SBD in CMS is built around a macrocycle engine that works backward from meet day. Hypertrophy,
              strength, peak, and taper phases are laid out based on the calendar so prep feels intentional.
            </p>
            <ul class="bullet-list">
              <li>Competition-date aware block sequencing</li>
              <li>Peak and taper logic that respects time to the platform</li>
              <li>A single home for squat, bench, deadlift, and meet-focused progression</li>
            </ul>
          </article>
        </div>
