<body>
  <div class="container">
    <nav class="site-header">
      <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem;">
        <a class="brand" href="/index.html" aria-label="Center Mass Strength home">
          <img src="../images/logo.png" alt="CM Strength .fit">
        </a>
      </div>
      <a href="/index.html#join-beta" class="launch-btn">CLAIM BETA SLOT</a>
    </nav>

    <header>
      <h1>Program Architectures</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">The Training Paths: Three Engines, One Goal—Your Best Strength</p>
    </header>

    <div class="nav-bar">
      <a href="/methodology/">Index</a>
      <a href="/methodology/macrocycle.html">Macrocycle</a>
      <a href="/methodology/the-load-engine.html">Load Engine</a>
      <a href="/methodology/readiness-and-rpee.html">Readiness</a>
      <a href="/methodology/weak-point-analysis.html">Weak Point</a>
      <a href="/methodology/joint-health-and-longevity.html">Joint Health</a>
    </div>

    <div class="lifters-note">
      <p>"Whether you want to be a bench specialist or a full-power monster, these architectures are the blueprints. We've pre-loaded the logic for each path so you can just show up and work."</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Three Paths</h2>

    <p>CMS offers three distinct program architectures, each optimized for different goals and athlete profiles:</p>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>1. Bench Specialization (13 Weeks)</h3>
      <p><strong>Focus:</strong> Maximize bench press 1RM only</p>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Bench-focused competitors, singles lifters, or those training between meets</p>
      <p><strong>Philosophy:</strong> Every session is bench-centric. Secondary lifts and accessories exist to support bench press gains, nothing else.</p>

      <h3>2. Jacked & Strong (12 Weeks)</h3>
      <p><strong>Focus:</strong> Balanced strength + hypertrophy across all lifts</p>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Accessory enthusiasts, body composition goals, sustainability-focused lifters</p>
      <p><strong>Philosophy:</strong> Strength on primary lifts meets meaningful hypertrophy on secondary/accessory work. Leads to muscular, capable athletes.</p>

      <h3>3. SBD Full Power (Adjustable 12–16 Weeks)</h3>
      <p><strong>Focus:</strong> Compete in all three lifts (squat, bench, deadlift)</p>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Full powerlifting meets, well-rounded strength athletes</p>
      <p><strong>Philosophy:</strong> Rotates through focused blocks for each lift while maintaining baseline competency in others. Meet prep for the complete package.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>How the Engines Differ by Path</h2>

    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Engine Aspect</th>
        <th>Bench Spec</th>
        <th>Jacked & Strong</th>
        <th>SBD</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Primary Lift</td>
        <td>Bench Press</td>
        <td>All three (rotating)</td>
        <td>All three (cycling)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Secondary Lifts</td>
        <td>1 (weak-point-specific bench variant)</td>
        <td>2–3 (varied, accessory-heavy)</td>
        <td>1 per lift (squat, bench, dead variants)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Accessory Volume</td>
        <td>Low (support bench only)</td>
        <td>High (hypertrophy focus)</td>
        <td>Moderate (balanced across lifts)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>RPE Range</td>
        <td>6–9 (intensity emphasis)</td>
        <td>6–8 (moderate, sustainable)</td>
        <td>6–9 (block-dependent)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Meet Readiness</td>
        <td>Bench competition only</td>
        <td>General strength (no meet prep)</td>
        <td>Full three-lift competition</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Program Comparison Matrix</h2>

    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Aspect</th>
        <th>Bench Spec</th>
        <th>Jacked & Strong</th>
        <th>SBD</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Cycle Length</td>
        <td>Fixed 13 weeks</td>
        <td>Fixed 12 weeks</td>
        <td>Adjustable 12–16 weeks</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Weekly Sessions</td>
        <td>3, 4, or 5 days</td>
        <td>3, 4, or 5 days</td>
        <td>4 or 5 days</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Deload Week Frequency</td>
        <td>Every 4 weeks (weeks 4, 8, 12)</td>
        <td>Every 4 weeks (weeks 4, 8, 12)</td>
        <td>Every 4 weeks (block gates)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Joint Health Monitoring</td>
        <td>Yes (shoulder, elbow, wrist)</td>
        <td>Yes (all joints)</td>
        <td>Yes (all joints)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Weak Point Routing</td>
        <td>Bench-only specialization</td>
        <td>Light weak-point focus</td>
        <td>Per-lift specialization (squat, bench, dead)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Expected 1RM Gain</td>
        <td>+15–30 lbs</td>
        <td>+10–20 lbs (balanced)</td>
        <td>+10–25 lbs (depends on main lift)</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Real-World Example: SBD Meet Prep (16-Week Timeline)</h2>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>Athlete Profile</h3>
      <p>Marcus, raw powerlifter: Bench 405, Squat 500, Deadlift 600. Total: 1505 lbs. Meet in 16 weeks.</p>

      <h3>Week 1–4: Squat Block (Skill)</h3>
      <p>Focus: Squat technique and positioning. Bench and deadlift maintained at moderate volume.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Main: Squat 3×5 @ RPE 6–7</li>
        <li>Secondary: Box Squat (weak-point-specific) 3×5 @ RPE 6.5</li>
        <li>Bench: 2×4 @ RPE 6 (maintenance)</li>
        <li>Deadlift: 1×5 @ RPE 6 (maintenance)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Week 5–8: Bench Block (Strength)</h3>
      <p>Focus: Bench press strength and volume. Squat and deadlift maintained.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Main: Bench 3×4 @ RPE 7–8</li>
        <li>Secondary: Incline Bench (weak-point-specific) 3×4 @ RPE 7.5</li>
        <li>Squat: 2×3 @ RPE 6.5 (maintenance)</li>
        <li>Deadlift: 1×3 @ RPE 6.5 (maintenance)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Week 9–12: Deadlift Block (Peak)</h3>
      <p>Focus: Deadlift intensity and competition readiness. Squat and bench taper slightly.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Main: Deadlift 2×3, 1×1 @ RPE 8–9</li>
        <li>Secondary: Speed Deadlift 3×2 @ RPE 7</li>
        <li>Squat: 2×2 @ RPE 7 (taper)</li>
        <li>Bench: 2×2 @ RPE 7 (taper)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Week 13–14: Deload + Final Taper</h3>
      <p>Recovery week. All RPE 5–6, reduced volume. Prepare body for opener attempts.</p>

      <h3>Week 15–16: Meet Week</h3>
      <p>Opener attempts on all three lifts. Attempt selection based on readiness and recent performance.</p>

      <h3>Result</h3>
      <p>Marcus arrives at the meet with a balanced, periodized build: Squat +20 lbs (520), Bench +15 lbs (420), Deadlift +25 lbs (625). Total: 1565 lbs (+60 lbs from baseline).</p>
    </div>

    <h2>How to Choose Your Path</h2>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>Choose Bench Specialization If:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You compete (or want to compete) in bench-only competitions</li>
        <li>Your primary goal is a bigger bench press</li>
        <li>You have limited training time (3 days/week) and want to maximize bench progress</li>
        <li>You're willing to sacrifice squat/deadlift development for bench gains</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Choose Jacked & Strong If:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You want balanced strength + muscle growth across all lifts</li>
        <li>You prioritize body composition and aesthetics alongside strength</li>
        <li>You enjoy variety in exercises and don't have a specific meet goal</li>
        <li>You want a sustainable, long-term training path without peaking</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Choose SBD Full Power If:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You compete in full powerlifting (or want to prepare for it)</li>
        <li>You want competitive totals in all three lifts</li>
        <li>You like periodized blocks with clear phases for each lift</li>
        <li>You have 4–5 days per week to train</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Switching Programs Mid-Cycle</h2>

    <p>You can switch programs at block gates (end of week 4, 8, 12). When you switch:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Current 1RMs are preserved:</strong> Your estimated maxes carry over, so load calculations continue logically</li>
      <li><strong>Block progression resets:</strong> You start the new program at Block 1 (Skill) of the new architecture</li>
      <li><strong>Weak point re-assessment is recommended:</strong> Different programs have different weak-point routing, so reassess if switching to SBD</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-point">
      <strong>Example:</strong> You finish a Bench Specialization cycle (Bench +25 lbs). You want to try Jacked & Strong. At the block gate, you switch. Your bench 1RM carries over, and you begin Jacked & Strong Block 1 with new exercise variety and higher accessory volume.
    </div>

    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>Three program architectures: Bench Spec (bench-focused), Jacked & Strong (balanced), SBD (full powerlifting)</li>
      <li>Each program uses the same adaptive engines (load, readiness, weak point, joint health)</li>
      <li>Choose based on your goals, training frequency, and competition style</li>
      <li>Switch programs at block gates without losing progress</li>
      <li>All programs include autoregulation, joint monitoring, and intelligent adaptation</li>
    </ul>

      </div> <!-- End container -->

