    <header>
      <h1>Load Engine</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">The Math: Algorithmic Weight Selection Beyond Static Percentages</p>
    </header>

    <div class="nav-bar">
      <a href="/methodology/">Index</a>
      <a href="/methodology/macrocycle.html">Macrocycle</a>
      <a href="/methodology/readiness-and-rpee.html">Readiness</a>
      <a href="/methodology/weak-point-analysis.html">Weak Point</a>
      <a href="/methodology/joint-health-and-longevity.html">Joint Health</a>
      <a href="/methodology/program-architectures.html">Programs</a>
    </div>

    <div class="lifters-note">
      <p>"Static percentages are a lie because your strength changes daily. This engine calculates your weights in real-time, ensuring the bar is heavy enough to trigger growth but light enough to keep you moving."</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Beyond Static Percentages</h2>
    <p>Traditional periodization uses fixed percentages: 70% for a 5-rep set, 80% for a 3-rep set, etc. These are one-size-fits-all prescriptions that ignore individual variation, fatigue state, and training history.</p>

    <p><strong>CMS rejects this approach.</strong> Instead, it uses RPE (Rate of Perceived Exertion) as the primary metric and calculates actual load dynamically based on your estimated 1RM (e1RM), recent performance, and readiness score.</p>

    <h2>The Load Calculation Algorithm (4-Step Process)</h2>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>Step 1: Determine e1RM (Estimated 1 Rep Max)</h3>
      <p>CMS uses the <strong>Brzycki formula</strong> to estimate your 1RM based on your last successful heavy lift:</p>
      
      <div class="algorithm-box">
        e1RM = Weight ÷ (1.0278 − 0.0278 × Reps)
      </div>

      <p><strong>Example:</strong> If you lifted 315 lbs for 3 reps, your e1RM = 315 ÷ (1.0278 − 0.0834) = 315 ÷ 0.9444 = <strong>333.5 lbs</strong></p>

      <p>This e1RM is recalculated after every top set logged in the app. It's your current strength ceiling.</p>

      <h3>Step 2: RPE → Percent Conversion</h3>
      <p>Your prescribed RPE (e.g., RPE 7) is converted to a percentage of e1RM using a standard table:</p>

      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>RPE</th>
          <th>1 Rep</th>
          <th>2 Reps</th>
          <th>3 Reps</th>
          <th>5 Reps</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>6</td>
          <td>85%</td>
          <td>82%</td>
          <td>80%</td>
          <td>76%</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>7</td>
          <td>90%</td>
          <td>87%</td>
          <td>85%</td>
          <td>81%</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>8</td>
          <td>93%</td>
          <td>91%</td>
          <td>88%</td>
          <td>85%</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>9</td>
          <td>97%</td>
          <td>95%</td>
          <td>92%</td>
          <td>90%</td>
        </tr>
      </table>

      <h3>Step 3: Calculate Raw Weight</h3>
      <p>Multiply the RPE-derived percent by your e1RM:</p>
      <div class="algorithm-box">
        Raw Weight = e1RM × Percent
      </div>

      <p><strong>Example:</strong> e1RM = 333.5 lbs, RPE 8 for 3 reps = 88% → 333.5 × 0.88 = <strong>293.5 lbs</strong></p>

      <h3>Step 4: Round to Nearest 5 lbs</h3>
      <p>All prescribed weights are rounded to the nearest 5 lbs for loading convenience. 293.5 lbs becomes <strong>295 lbs</strong> (or 290 lbs, depending on direction).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="key-point">
      <strong>Why 5-lb Increments?</strong> Most commercial barbells and gym setups use 5-lb plates. Rounding to 5-lb increments ensures your prescribed load is loadable without fractions or improvisation.
    </div>

    <h2>Load Selection by Block Type</h2>

    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Block</th>
        <th>Top Set RPE</th>
        <th>Backdown RPE</th>
        <th>Purpose</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Skill</td>
        <td>6–7</td>
        <td>6–6.5</td>
        <td>Work capacity, technique</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Strength</td>
        <td>7–8</td>
        <td>7–7.5</td>
        <td>Volume + load</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Peak</td>
        <td>8–9</td>
        <td>7–8</td>
        <td>Intensity, competition prep</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Test</td>
        <td>Variable</td>
        <td>N/A</td>
        <td>Max attempt</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Real-Time Recalculation: Backdown Logic</h2>

    <p>After you complete your top set, the app recalculates the backdown sets based on your <strong>actual top set weight</strong>, not the prescribed weight.</p>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>Example Scenario</h3>
      <p><strong>Prescribed Top Set:</strong> 295 lbs × 3 reps @ RPE 8</p>
      <p><strong>What You Actually Lifted:</strong> 300 lbs × 3 reps @ RPE 7 (felt easier)</p>
      <p><strong>Backdown Prescription (RPE 7):</strong> 300 × 0.85 = 255 lbs</p>

      <p>The app recalculates your backdowns using the actual 300 lbs, not the prescribed 295 lbs. This ensures backdowns are responsive to real performance, not stale prescriptions.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Movement-Specific History</h2>

    <p>CMS tracks performance on every exercise independently. Your bench press e1RM is separate from your dumbbell flye e1RM. When you return to an exercise after a layoff, the app remembers your prior peak performance and uses that as a starting point—not a reset to zero.</p>

    <h2>Traditional vs. CMS Comparison</h2>

    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Aspect</th>
        <th>Traditional Periodization</th>
        <th>CMS Load Engine</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Weight Selection</td>
        <td>Fixed percentage (80% of preset max)</td>
        <td>RPE-based, e1RM-derived</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Adaptation to Fatigue</td>
        <td>Manual adjustment by lifter</td>
        <td>Automatic adjustment via readiness score</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Backdown Adjustment</td>
        <td>Pre-prescribed, fixed</td>
        <td>Recalculated after top set</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Exercise History</td>
        <td>Rarely tracked per movement</td>
        <td>Complete history per movement</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>User Burden</td>
        <td>Manual % calculation</td>
        <td>Prescribed automatically</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>Load = RPE → Percent → e1RM × Percent → Round to 5 lbs</li>
      <li>e1RM updates after every top set based on Brzycki formula</li>
      <li>Backdowns recalculate in real-time based on actual top set weight</li>
      <li>Each exercise tracked independently—no cross-movement assumptions</li>
      <li>All math is transparent and auditable in your session data</li>
    </ul>

