    <header>
      <h1>Weak Point Analysis</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">The Specialization: Surgical Exercise Routing Based on Your Sticking Point</p>
    </header>

    <div class="nav-bar">
      <a href="/methodology/">Index</a>
      <a href="/methodology/macrocycle.html">Macrocycle</a>
      <a href="/methodology/the-load-engine.html">Load Engine</a>
      <a href="/methodology/readiness-and-rpee.html">Readiness</a>
      <a href="/methodology/joint-health-and-longevity.html">Joint Health</a>
      <a href="/methodology/program-architectures.html">Programs</a>
    </div>

    <div class="lifters-note">
      <p>"Everyone stalls. This engine identifies exactly where your lift is failing and automatically swaps in the movements proven to blast through that specific plateau."</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Three Weak Points</h2>

    <p>Every bench presser has a sticking point—a range where the bar slows or stops. CMS categorizes these into three archetypal weak points:</p>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>1. Off-Chest (Bottom Position)</h3>
      <p>The bar stalls immediately after leaving the chest. You lack the explosive power from the bottom, or your chest/front delts aren't driving hard enough.</p>
      <p><strong>Secondary Lift:</strong> Spoto Press (paused, 1 inch off chest)</p>
      <p><strong>Accessory:</strong> Dumbbell Flyes 2×12 (pec activation, range of motion)</p>

      <h3>2. Mid-Range (Stall Midway)</h3>
      <p>The bar moves well off the chest, but stalls 2–4 inches up. You lack midrange strength or scapular stability.</p>
      <p><strong>Secondary Lift:</strong> Pause Bench (2 sec pause midway) or 2″ Board Press</p>
      <p><strong>Accessory:</strong> Seal Rows 2×10 (scapular stability, back strength)</p>

      <h3>3. Lockout (Top Position)</h3>
      <p>The bar moves well until near the top, then stalls. Your triceps and front delts lack lockout strength.</p>
      <p><strong>Secondary Lift:</strong> Close-Grip Bench Press (triceps emphasis)</p>
      <p><strong>Accessory:</strong> Skull Crushers 2×10 (triceps isolation, lockout strength)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="key-point">
      <strong>No Weak Point?</strong> If you're balanced across all ranges, CMS defaults to the Larsen Press (a neutral-grip strength builder) with no specific accessory.
    </div>

    <h2>The Weak Point Selection Flow</h2>

    <p>You identify your weak point during <strong>onboarding</strong> (Week 1 of your first program). CMS asks you to describe where the bar stalls, then maps your answer to one of the three categories.</p>

    <p>After the first block, you can <strong>reassess</strong> at a block gate. Did your off-chest weakness improve? Switch to mid-range focus. This flexibility allows CMS to adapt to your progress.</p>

    <h2>How CMS Routes Exercises</h2>

    <p>The weak point directly determines exercise selection in two ways:</p>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>1. Secondary Lift Selection (Skill & Strength Blocks)</h3>
      <p>Your secondary lift rotates based on weak point and block type:</p>

      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Weak Point</th>
          <th>Skill Block Secondary</th>
          <th>Strength Block Secondary</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Off-Chest</td>
          <td>Spoto Press</td>
          <td>Competition Bench</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Mid-Range</td>
          <td>Pause Bench (2 sec)</td>
          <td>2″ Board Press</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Lockout</td>
          <td>Close-Grip Bench</td>
          <td>Close-Grip Bench</td>
        </tr>
      </table>

      <h3>2. Accessory Selection</h3>
      <p>Accessories are paired with the secondary lift to reinforce weak-point-specific adaptation:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Off-chest:</strong> Flyes (chest range)</li>
        <li><strong>Mid-range:</strong> Rows (scapular stability)</li>
        <li><strong>Lockout:</strong> Skull Crushers (triceps)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Real-World Example: Off-Chest Case Study</h2>

    <div class="content-block">
      <h3>Lifter Profile</h3>
      <p>Jake, bench press 1RM: 315 lbs. Bar stalls 1–2 inches off the chest.</p>

      <h3>Week 1 (Skill Block)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Main: Bench Press 5×5 @ RPE 6–7</li>
        <li>Secondary: Spoto Press (paused 1 inch off chest) 4×5 @ RPE 6.5</li>
        <li>Accessory: Dumbbell Flyes 2×12 @ RPE 5–6</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The Spoto Press trains the bottom-range explosiveness. Flyes activate the pecs through a larger range of motion.</p>

      <h3>Week 5 (Strength Block)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Main: Bench Press 4×4 @ RPE 7–8</li>
        <li>Secondary: Competition Bench (full range) 3×3 @ RPE 7.5</li>
        <li>Accessory: Dumbbell Flyes 2×12 @ RPE 5–6</li>
      </ul>

      <p>By now, Spoto Press weakness has mostly resolved. The program shifts to competition bench at higher intensity, maintaining flyes for pec drive and resilience.</p>

      <h3>Week 9 (Peak Block)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Main: Bench Press 3×3, 1×1 @ RPE 8–9</li>
        <li>Secondary: Heavy Bench Competition Variation 2×2 @ RPE 8.5</li>
        <li>Accessory: Dumbbell Flyes 2×8 (heavier weight) @ RPE 6–7</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The focus shifts to meet-specific intensity. Off-chest strength is now solid; CMS reinforces it with heavier flyes to maintain pec resilience.</p>

      <h3>Result</h3>
      <p>After 13 weeks, Jake's competition bench (bottom-range drive + full-range power) improved from 315 to 330 lbs—a 15-lb PR specifically in the weak point area.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Why This Works</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Specificity:</strong> Each weak point has a unique secondary lift that directly targets the sticking point range</li>
      <li><strong>Consistency:</strong> You address the same weakness every session (secondary lift + accessory), allowing adaptation</li>
      <li><strong>Data-Driven:</strong> Weak point routing is informed by bench press biomechanics research, not guesswork</li>
      <li><strong>Progressive Overload:</strong> As weakness improves, the program shifts focus, preventing plateau</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>Three archetypal weak points: off-chest, mid-range, lockout</li>
      <li>Each weak point has a specific secondary lift + accessory pairing</li>
      <li>Weak point selection happens at onboarding and can be reassessed at block gates</li>
      <li>Secondary lifts and accessories are automatically routed based on your weak point</li>
      <li>Specialization accelerates improvement in your specific sticking point</li>
    </ul>

